All a trademark grants is the right to prevent others from using the
same mark to denote their own products or services, in order to prevent
confusion in the public's mind.

This is a very narrowly defined right. It does NOT give you the right to
attempt to control speech or the evolution of the English language. It
is easy for a trademark HOLDER to lose a trademark if he/she/it doesn't
follow certain usage rules, but AT&amp;T lawyers notwithstanding, outsiders
are not obligated to put "TM" or anything else next to the character
string "UNIX".  The only thing they can't do is to use it to name their
own products or services.

Several years ago, George Lucas sued both a pro- and anti-SDI group,
accusing each of misusing his trademark "Star Wars". The judge threw out
the suit, basically for the reasons given above.

Phil

